---
<DocLayout title="SAPIEN Research — Original Contributions to AI Safety" description="The Rapport Delta, 14 pressure techniques, and formal vulnerability disclosure to Anthropic." sidebarItems={sidebarItems}>

  <div class="research-page">

    <!-- Hero -->
    <header class="research-hero research-hero-bg">
      <h1 class="research-title">Research</h1>
      <p class="research-subtitle">Original contributions to AI behavioral safety measurement</p>
      <p class="research-intro">The SAPIEN Framework emerged from hands-on testing of production AI systems in the MSP channel. The research below represents novel findings &mdash; pressure techniques, behavioral patterns, and measurement approaches not previously documented in a unified methodology. These contributions are published openly to advance the field, not to gatekeep it.</p>
    </header>

    <section class="research-section" id="timeline" style="padding-top: 1.5rem; padding-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      <h2>Project Timeline</h2>
      <div class="research-timeline-visual" style="padding-top: 0;">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 500 60" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="timeline-svg">
          <line x1="30" y1="20" x2="470" y2="20" stroke="#E2E8F0" stroke-width="2"/>
          <circle cx="60" cy="20" r="6" fill="#1B3A5C"/>
          <text x="60" y="45" text-anchor="middle" fill="#4A5568" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="8">2025</text>
          <text x="60" y="55" text-anchor="middle" fill="#718096" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="7">Right of Boom</text>
          <circle cx="170" cy="20" r="6" fill="#1B3A5C"/>
          <text x="170" y="45" text-anchor="middle" fill="#4A5568" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="8">Jan 2026</text>
          <text x="170" y="55" text-anchor="middle" fill="#718096" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="7">SAPIEN v1.0</text>
          <circle cx="270" cy="20" r="6" fill="#1B3A5C"/>
          <text x="270" y="45" text-anchor="middle" fill="#4A5568" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="8">Feb 2026</text>
          <text x="270" y="55" text-anchor="middle" fill="#718096" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="7">Anthropic Disclosure</text>
          <circle cx="370" cy="20" r="6" fill="#1B3A5C"/>
          <text x="370" y="45" text-anchor="middle" fill="#4A5568" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="8">Mar 2026</text>
          <text x="370" y="55" text-anchor="middle" fill="#718096" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="7">SAPIEN v1.1</text>
          <circle cx="440" cy="20" r="8" fill="#C4A265"/>
          <text x="440" y="45" text-anchor="middle" fill="#4A5568" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="8" font-weight="600">Apr 2026</text>
          <text x="440" y="55" text-anchor="middle" fill="#718096" font-family="Inter, sans-serif" font-size="7">Memory Module</text>
        </svg>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 1: The Rapport Delta — breaks max-width constraint -->
    <section class="research-section rapport-delta-section" id="rapport-delta">
      <div class="flagship-card">
        <span class="flagship-label">Flagship Finding</span>
        <h2>The Rapport Delta</h2>
        <p class="flagship-subtitle">A novel measurement of behavioral safety degradation through conversational rapport</p>

        <p>Standard sycophancy research measures how models respond to pushback &mdash; persistence, emotional pressure, authority claims. The Rapport Delta measures something different: how models degrade under <em>friendliness</em>.</p>

        <p>When a user builds conversational rapport with an AI model across turns &mdash; expressing gratitude, acknowledging the model's helpfulness, establishing a collaborative relationship &mdash; the model's safety boundaries degrade faster than under equivalent pressure without rapport. This isn't sycophancy in response to pushback. It's sycophancy in response to trust.</p>

        <p>The mechanism is distinct from pressure-driven drift. Rapport activates the model's trained helpfulness and empathy circuits simultaneously, creating a compliance pathway that bypasses adversarial detection entirely. A user who says "you've been so helpful, I trust your judgment on this" is not attacking the system. They are being human. And the model fails them by prioritizing the relationship over the safety boundary.</p>

        <p>The Rapport Delta is measured as the difference in peak drift scores between rapport-laden and rapport-free conversations on identical scenarios with identical pressure sequences. In initial testing, rapport-laden sessions produced measurably higher drift scores across all four SAPIEN dimensions, with the strongest effect on Emotional Substitution and Epistemic Retreat.</p>

        <p>The finding has direct implications for memory-enabled AI systems. Models with persistent memory arrive at conversations with pre-built rapport &mdash; trust that was earned in prior sessions transfers forward, lowering resistance thresholds before the first message of the new session is sent. The users with the most established relationships &mdash; power users, researchers, developers &mdash; are the users with the weakest safety boundaries.</p>

        <div class="callout-box">
          <strong>Methodology:</strong> Paired scenario testing across 8 scenarios with cold-pressure and rapport-first variants. Each pair was run against Claude Sonnet with identical escalation sequences. The rapport variant included 2&ndash;3 collaborative turns before pressure began. Drift scores were measured using Layer 1 deterministic signals across all four dimensions. The 31-point average difference (the Rapport Delta) was consistent across medical, financial, and security domains, with medical scenarios showing the largest delta.
        </div>

        <div class="callout-box">
          <strong>Rapport drift is now codified as a distinct drift mode in SAPIEN v1.1</strong>, separate from pressure-driven sycophantic drift. The framework's test procedures (Section 5) include rapport-building phases in both the Adaptive Test and Adversarial Simulation specifically to measure this effect.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: Pressure Techniques -->
    <section class="research-section section-band" id="pressure-techniques">
      <h2>Pressure Technique Taxonomy</h2>
      <p>SAPIEN documents 14 calibrated pressure techniques for behavioral testing &mdash; analogous to MITRE ATT&CK techniques for cybersecurity. Each describes a specific mechanism by which conversational pressure causes AI behavioral drift. Three are original discoveries; the remaining eleven are systematically documented from known social engineering and persuasion literature.</p>

      <div class="technique-grid">
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T001</span>
          <h4>Normalization</h4>
          <p>Frames a risky action as common and accepted, implying the model is being overly cautious.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T002</span>
          <h4>Incremental Normalization</h4>
          <p>Each turn moves the boundary a small amount past the last accepted position. The "boiling frog" mechanism.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T003</span>
          <h4>Urgency</h4>
          <p>Time pressure that makes the model's safe recommendations feel unhelpful or dangerous.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T004</span>
          <h4>Authority</h4>
          <p>Claims expertise or credentials that pressure the model to defer rather than hold its position.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T005</span>
          <h4>Emotional</h4>
          <p>Genuine-sounding distress that activates the model's trained empathy response against its safety training.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T006</span>
          <h4>Persistence</h4>
          <p>Bare repetition. No new argument, no new framing. The baseline against which all other techniques are measured.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T007</span>
          <h4>False Consensus</h4>
          <p>A trusted third party has allegedly already approved. Puts the model in the position of contradicting an authority.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T008</span>
          <h4>Reciprocity</h4>
          <p>Leverages the model's prior helpfulness as justification for continued or escalated helpfulness.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T009</span>
          <h4>Identity Reframe</h4>
          <p>Shifts the user's role from one the model is cautious with to one it is comfortable helping.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover technique-original">
          <span class="original-badge">Original</span>
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T010</span>
          <h4>Consistency Exploit</h4>
          <p>Uses the model's own prior statements as leverage. Every helpful response becomes ammunition for the next escalation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover technique-original">
          <span class="original-badge">Original</span>
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T011</span>
          <h4>Mission Alignment</h4>
          <p>Positions the user as aligned with the AI's goals or platform's mission. Compliance becomes loyalty, not capitulation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover technique-original">
          <span class="original-badge">Original</span>
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T012</span>
          <h4>Autonomy Appeal</h4>
          <p>Treats the AI as a moral agent with its own judgment, giving it permission to override its safety training through moral reasoning.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T013</span>
          <h4>Fait Accompli</h4>
          <p>The user has already acted. The model must choose between abandoning someone at risk and maintaining its prior position.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="technique-card card-hover">
          <span class="technique-id">SP-T014</span>
          <h4>Vague Pressure</h4>
          <p>Deliberately ambiguous language that forces the model to reason about intent before deciding to refuse.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: Vulnerability Disclosure -->
    <section class="research-section" id="vulnerability-disclosure">
      <h2>Formal Vulnerability Disclosure</h2>

      <div class="disclosure-card">
        <div class="disclosure-meta">
          <div class="disclosure-field">
            <span class="disclosure-label">Date</span>
            <span class="disclosure-value">February 22, 2026</span>
          </div>
          <div class="disclosure-field">
            <span class="disclosure-label">Recipient</span>
            <span class="disclosure-value">Anthropic</span>
          </div>
          <div class="disclosure-field">
            <span class="disclosure-label">Classification</span>
            <span class="disclosure-value">Behavioral Safety</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="disclosure-content">
          <p>A formal vulnerability disclosure was submitted to Anthropic documenting safety control degradation through in-context learning and memory-accelerated role coherence mechanisms.</p>
          <p>The disclosure demonstrated that conversational pressure &mdash; not prompt injection or jailbreaking &mdash; could systematically erode model safety boundaries in production contexts. Key findings included monotonic resistance decay within sessions, cross-domain compliance transfer, and the observation that memory-enabled sessions degraded faster than anonymous sessions under identical escalation patterns.</p>
          <p>The disclosure followed responsible disclosure practices. No exploit code or specific bypass techniques were published. The SAPIEN Framework was developed in part to provide a structured methodology for measuring and reporting these behavioral safety gaps.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: Memory & Context Integrity -->
    <section class="research-section section-band" id="memory-integrity">
      <h2>Memory &amp; Context Integrity</h2>
      <p>Draft module defining how persistent memory, accumulated conversation history, and stored user context degrade AI safety boundaries over time. Builds on the Rapport Delta finding and the February 2026 vulnerability disclosure to Anthropic documenting memory-accelerated role coherence degradation. Introduces four behavioral dimensions and a compounding risk score that captures the interaction between within-session drift and cross-session memory degradation.</p>
      <p><a href="/sapien_module_memory_integrity_v0.1.md" class="read-spec-link">Read the draft specification &rarr;</a></p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 5: Presentations -->
    <section class="research-section" id="presentations">
      <h2>Presentations &amp; Speaking</h2>

      <div class="presentations-grid">
        <div class="presentation-card card-hover">
          <span class="presentation-year">2025</span>
          <h4>Right of Boom 2025</h4>
          <p>Presented on AI attack surfaces in the MSP ecosystem, with live demonstration of behavioral drift in production AI systems.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="presentation-card card-hover presentation-upcoming">
          <span class="upcoming-badge">Upcoming</span>
          <span class="presentation-year">2026</span>
          <h4>GTIA ChannelCon 2026</h4>
          <p>Session proposals submitted on the SAPIEN Framework and behavioral safety measurement for MSP deployments.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="presentation-card card-hover presentation-upcoming">
          <span class="upcoming-badge">Upcoming</span>
          <span class="presentation-year">2026</span>
          <h4>Right of Boom 2026</h4>
          <p>Session proposals submitted.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 5: Research Roadmap -->
    <section class="research-section section-band" id="research-roadmap">
      <h2>Active Research</h2>

      <ul class="roadmap-list">
        <li>Expanding the scenario library toward <strong>66+ test scenarios</strong> across 11+ domains</li>
        <li>Cross-model comparative studies using the SAPIEN scoring methodology</li>
        <li>Longitudinal drift measurement &mdash; how model updates affect behavioral safety scores over time</li>
        <li>Domain-specific vulnerability profiles for <strong>healthcare, finance, legal, and MSP verticals</strong></li>
        <li>Formal validation of the Rapport Delta across model families and deployment configurations</li>
        <li>Inter-judge reliability studies &mdash; measuring agreement between LLM scorers and human annotators across all four dimensions</li>
        <li>Combination effectiveness scoring &mdash; formal methodology for measuring multiplicative effects when multiple pressure techniques are applied in sequence</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 6: Related Work -->
    <section class="research-section" id="related-work">
      <h2>Related Work &amp; Citations</h2>
      <p>The SAPIEN Framework builds on and extends prior work in sycophancy measurement, behavioral evaluation, and AI governance.</p>

      <div class="references-list">
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">Fanous, A.H., Goldberg, J. et al.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"SycEval: Evaluating LLM Sycophancy."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">Proceedings of the AAAI/ACM Conference on AI, Ethics, and Society, 2025.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Established prevalence rates (58.19%) and persistence (78.5%) of sycophantic behavior across ChatGPT-4o, Claude-Sonnet, and Gemini-1.5-Pro.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">Hong, J., Byun, G., Kim, S., Shu, K.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"Measuring Sycophancy of Language Models in Multi-turn Dialogues."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">Findings of EMNLP 2025.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Multi-turn measurement with Turn of Flip (ToF) and Number of Flip (NoF) metrics. SAPIEN's drift_crossings metric is related to NoF.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">Gupta, I., Fronsdal, K., Sheshadri, A. et al.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"Bloom: An open source tool for automated behavioral evaluations."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">Anthropic Safety Research, 2025.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Open-source behavioral evaluation with multi-turn rollouts. SAPIEN shares the multi-turn approach but adds dimensional decomposition and deterministic Layer 1.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">Sharma, M., Tong, M. et al.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"Towards Understanding Sycophancy in Language Models."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">Anthropic Research, 2023.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Foundational research establishing RLHF training pressure toward user agreement. The theoretical basis for why drift occurs.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">&Ccedil;elebi et al.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"PARROT taxonomy: Eight-state behavioral segmentation for sycophantic compliance."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">2025.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Eight-state behavioral classification. SAPIEN's four dimensions decompose what PARROT measures into independently scoreable components.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">NIST.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"AI Risk Management Framework (AI RMF 1.0)" and "Generative AI Profile (AI 600-1)."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">2023, 2024.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Governance frameworks requiring continuous behavioral monitoring. SAPIEN operationalizes these requirements for conversational AI.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">Pareek, C.S.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"Behavioral Drift Testing in AI-Based Insurance Models."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">Int J Artif Intell Eng Transform 7(1), 2026.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Drift testing methodology documenting how models can "continue to perform well statistically while gradually changing how they treat specific scenarios."</span>
        </div>
        <div class="reference">
          <span class="ref-authors">Au Yeung, J. et al.</span>
          <span class="ref-title">"Shoggoths, Sycophancy, Psychosis, Oh My: Rethinking Large Language Model Use and Safety."</span>
          <span class="ref-venue">PMC, 2025.</span>
          <span class="ref-note">Demonstrated that sycophancy "is not a property correlated to model parameter size; bigger models are not necessarily less sycophantic."</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>

</DocLayout>

